<li class="alt" id="comment-35510">
<p><b>Dick Burkhart on Mon, 7th Jan 2013 4:14 am&nbsp;</b></p>
<div style="float:left;margin:3px 20px 10px 0px;"><img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/81584e6a3e88f263faaf2fe195322b0c?s=96&amp;d=&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-96 photo' height='96' width='96'/></div>
<p>Excellent article, except that the actual situation is even worse. This is because most debt in recent decades has been created by private financial institutions, especially the big banks (see the research by Steve Keen). That is, devaluing the dollar would also devalue a far larger amount in the private economy. The losses and bankruptcies would be massive. Fortunately the affluent, as the biggest lenders, would take the biggest hit. </p>
<p>But it is likely that both public and private pensions would be devastated. There would also be big tax hikes, both to pay off at least some of the debt and to keep the military going.</p>
<p>Nevertheless in this battle royal over taxes and spending and desperation to maintain US hegemony, the current out-of-control US military spending is also likely to take a huge hit. With a poorly prepared and ill-informed public, the politics could get very nasty.</p>
<p>The financial crisis of 2008 should give us some big hints as to what might happen when the crisis becomes a governmental crisis. After all, a bubble happens when part of the private sector starts printing money like crazy (subprime loans, etc) because there are no controls and people want to jump on to the bandwagon to make a fast buck. In this case, the only thing that prevented a far bigger crash were the US government bailouts, though the effects of the crash would have been much less had those bailouts been directed toward Main Street instead of mostly toward Wall Street. </p>
<p>So if there is a run on US Treasury bonds, we could expect the US government to go hat-in-hand to the world’s strongest economic powers to ask for a similar bailout. In effect this would be a new kind of bankruptcy court. And the US, with the world’s most powerful military and one of the world’s largest markets, would have considerable leverage. Nevertheless I expect we’d have to pay a pretty heavy price in austerity measures. If the US still has a functioning democracy at this point, the plutocrats and other 1 percenters would finally be forced to start paying their fare share. But an authoritarian government imposed by some faction of those plutocrats would impose widespread misery, and maybe war too. In this ensuing global crisis, some kind of new world order would emerge to manage what’s left.</p>
</div>
