<div class="commentleft">
<li class="alt" id="comment-35535">
<p><b>ken nohe on Mon, 7th Jan 2013 4:25 pm&nbsp;</b></p>
<div style="float:left;margin:3px 20px 10px 0px;"><img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/115e45607915788505f5b4493daf72ba?s=96&amp;d=&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-96 photo' height='96' width='96'/></div>
<p>Well, same as you Bill. You say it cannot last until 2020. I would tend to agree with that. But in between we cannot see anything clearly. It is unpredictable. </p>
<p>Where I think we disagree is about what comes next. I personally do not see &#8220;technicals&#8221; shooting at every moving object, the Somalia way in the streets of Chicago anytime soon. </p>
<p>I expect more &#8220;springs&#8221; in developing countries as the pressure increase. The divergence between have and have-not in developed countries will also increase. Incomes will keep declining and the decline can become rapid in some places threatening democracy. At some stage, inflation will roar back, and this is where the crash will be most visible because it will be very selective. </p>
<p>People will drive less, this is already the case amazingly in the US where we&#8217;re back to the mid 90s in miles driven per person. Flying will once again become a luxury. Exotic products will dwindle and the global production chain will make less and less sense. Tensions between countries will increase. But by then, we&#8217;ll be old and younger people will only have known &#8220;that&#8221;. People will be happy enough to have a job. Pension will become an &#8220;old&#8221; word and social security, well, go, get yourself treated in London if you want to see the future! </p>
<p>That is as far as I can see, in ten years maybe? OK, the blink of an eye for mankind but still 10 long years for us. Beyond that, it is very difficult to say anything. We will be 8 billion by then, and to my opinion, this is very close to maximum capacity. The Indonesian forests will be gone. The Amazon, dwindling, some parts of Africa, especially around the great lakes will be well beyond maximum capacity and one way or another, growth will stop. </p>
<p>Climate changes will increase the pressure, and dwindling oil resources will significantly decrease our incomes but fossil resources will still be very much there and amazingly the market will still be balanced, just at a very different level than today. People will still talk about the trillions of barrels available in the Green River and other shales areas but by then will realize that there is very little excess energy there once you input everything. Wind will have proved highly unreliable, solar will make some progress but people will realize that the problem of solar energy is to stock it when th sun doesn&#8217;t shine, which on average happens once a day wherever you live, and which adds a lot to the cost of that energy. </p>
<p>But by then, our world will become more and more virtual. No more books, DVD, CD but also less travel for business or leisure. Far less lighting with LEDs. Fewer factories too, as you will buy and download objects from the net that your 3D printer will create. And as energy dwindle, we will excel once again at using less and less. Everything will suddenly become smaller: you car, your home, your hamburger at Macdonald! I see a downsized future, but not Armageddon. And people will get used to it. Maybe not you and me, but the next generation: most certainly.</p>
</div>
